    "summary": "The Foundation of Syracuse (734 BC) by Corinthian colonists led by the oikist Archias was the establishment of what would become the largest and most powerful Greek city in the western Mediterranean. Located on the southeastern coast of Sicily on a natural harbor island (Ortygia) connected to the mainland, Syracuse combined ideal harbor conditions, fertile agricultural hinterland, and a defensible position that made it naturally suited to becoming a major power.\n\nOver the following centuries, Syracuse grew from a colony to an empire in miniature under its series of powerful tyrants — [[event:1988|Foundation of Syracuse]]'s Gelon (who defeated the Carthaginian invasion at Himera in 480 BC on the same day as Salamis, according to tradition), Hiero I (patron of Pindar and Aeschylus), Dionysius I (who built the largest empire in the Greek West), and Dionysius II. The city's defeat of the massive Athenian expedition (415–413 BC) was one of the greatest military reversals in ancient history, destroying an Athenian force of over 40,000 men in Sicily. Syracuse was eventually taken by Rome after the [[event:3817|Siege of Syracuse]] (212 BC), ending its independent history, but its cultural legacy — Archimedes, Theocritus, the Sicilian Greek tradition — was enormous.",
